[This page|https://developer.atlassian.com/static/connect/docs/scopes/confluence-rest-scopes.html] mentions two endpoints that look useful:

* {{/rest/prototype/\{version}/search}}
* {{/rest/searchv3/\{version}/search}}

We're thinking of using them for our product integration with Confluence (e.g. show the user a list of pages in a space).

Somebody at the Summit mentioned that they (or at least one of these) are safe to use, can you mark them as public in that case?

Make Connect Blueprints dynamic such that data can be remotely fetched and populated at the time of page creation.

h3. Descriptor
{code}
{
  template: {
    "url": "/mytemplate.xml,  // this is the existing blueprint url in the descriptor
  }

  "blueprintContext": { // url to POST to to obtain the variables for substitution in the blueprint
    "url": "/context"
  }, 
  // These are existing fields that will not be modified
  "createResult": "edit",
  "key": "remote-blueprint",
  "name": {
    "value": "Simple Remote Blueprint"
  }
}
{code}

h3. Data POSTED to the ContextData url
{code}
{
   parentPageId : "123456",
   spaceKey  : "DEMO",
   blueprintKey: "the-blueprint-key", 
   userKey : "12a3e457f6723b414c12e", 
   userLocale : "en_US"
}
{code}

h3. Shape of the data required to be returned from the contextData url
Similar to Dynamic Content Macro parameters: https://developer.atlassian.com/static/connect/docs/latest/modules/confluence/dynamic-content-macro.html
{code}

// Array<BlueprintContextValue>
[ 
  {
    "identifier": "ContentPageTitle", // Reserved variable for blueprints would also be here
    "value": "Page Title Name"
  },
  { "identifier": "param1",
    "value": ""bar"" // representation is implicitly 'plain'
  },
  { 
    "identifier": "param2",
    "value": "baz",
    "representation": "storage" | "wiki" | "plain"
  }
]
{code}

----

see https://pug.jira-dev.com/wiki/display/CP/Spec%3A+Dynamic+Blueprints

Space Tools Tabs are now evaluating conditions on their iframes, but the context is not being adequately populated for some condition types. e.g.

{code:}
        "conditions": [
          {
            "condition": "space_function_permission",
            "params": {
              "permission": "SETSPACEPERMISSIONS"
            }
          }
        ],
{code}

will always evaluate to false, whereas previously it was always evaluating to true.

On Confluence Cloud the web-item (and byline) module no longer seem to respect the size information for their icons: The HTML elements no longer have the width and height attributes they used to have.

This only happens for some users apparently. On systems where the icons are sized correctly the width and height HTML attributes ARE present.

See the attached screenshots.

We're using 32x32px images and specify a size of 16 pixels because they look much better on HiDPI screens.

We're adding web-items with icon sizes as described here:
https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/confluence/modules/web-item/

{code}
"webItems": [
	{
		"key": "web-item-export-pdf-launcher",
		"name": {
			"value": "Export to PDF"
		},
		"icon": {
			"width": 16,
			"height": 16,
			"url": "/static/assets/images/pdf/PDF_white_16px.svg"
		},
		...
	},
	...
}
{code}

When the following code is executed, the label "willBeLost" is not present on the page after the move:

labelManager.addLabel((Labelable) page, new Label("willBeRetained"));
labelManager.addLabel((Labelable) page, new Label("willBeLost"));
pageManager.movePageAsChild(page, parentTargetPage);

(this is inside a class declared as "extends ConfluenceActionSupport implements PageControl, PageAware, Beanable; labelManager and pageManager are set by dependency injection)

